    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-01-30T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-01-30T13:00:00-05:00" n="91"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d91">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/3162</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-01-30T19:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 30, 1917, 7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received January 31, 3.36 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4957. Saw <persName corresp="#p_ZDA1">Zimmermann</persName> this afternoon, 6
                    o’clock. He told me that <persName corresp="#p_BJHC1">Bernstorff</persName> had
                    informed him that he had delivered to you the memorandum referred to my 4925 and
                    my 4951 about armed merchant vessels, also that <persName corresp="#p_BJHC1"
                        >Bernstorff</persName> has given you Germany’s terms of peace.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d91fn1">See <persName corresp="#p_BJHC1">Bernstorff</persName>’s
                        letter to Colonel <persName corresp="#p_HEM1">House</persName>, Jan. 31,
                        1917, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_34">p. 34</ref>.</note>
                    I am sorry I have not been informed of situation because I am sure that Germany
                    now intends to immediately start reckless submarine warfare and blockade of
                    England by submarine boats, firing at sight on all ships. <persName
                        corresp="#p_ZDA1">Zimmermann</persName> told me the answer of the Entente to
                    Germany’s proposals and the nasty answer to the President had decided them, that
                    food would not hold out a year, and that they have only delayed out of
                    consideration for us, and that the Allies were preparing a great offensive on
                    all fronts. He said that I would get note to-morrow answering President’s speech
                    and declaring for the use of the submarine arm and blockade of England.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
